</div><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Color model based on red, green and blue</div>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1320445320">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}@media print{body.ns-0 .mw-parser-output .hatnote{display:none!important}}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"RGB" redirects here. For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/RGB_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="RGB (disambiguation)">RGB (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/RBG" class="mw-redirect" title="RBG">RBG</a>.</div>
<p class="mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Barn_grand_tetons_rgb_separation.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Barn_grand_tetons_rgb_separation.jpg/250px-Barn_grand_tetons_rgb_separation.jpg" decoding="async" width="180" height="538" style="--mw-file-upright: 0.7" class="mw-file-element mw-file-upright" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Barn_grand_tetons_rgb_separation.jpg/500px-Barn_grand_tetons_rgb_separation.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1600" data-file-height="4780" /></a><figcaption>Full color image along with its R, G, and B components</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><span><video id="mwe_player_0" poster="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv/250px--Additive_colors.ogv.jpg" controls="" preload="none" data-mw-tmh="" class="mw-file-element" width="250" height="141" data-durationhint="59" data-mwtitle="Additive_colors.ogv" data-mwprovider="wikimediacommons" resource="/wiki/File:Additive_colors.ogv"><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv/Additive_colors.ogv.480p.vp9.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=&quot;vp9, opus&quot;" data-transcodekey="480p.vp9.webm" data-width="854" data-height="480" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv" type="video/ogg; codecs=&quot;theora&quot;" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv/Additive_colors.ogv.1080p.vp9.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=&quot;vp9, opus&quot;" data-transcodekey="1080p.vp9.webm" data-width="1920" data-height="1080" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv/Additive_colors.ogv.144p.mjpeg.mov" type="video/quicktime" data-transcodekey="144p.mjpeg.mov" data-width="256" data-height="144" /><source src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/3/3d/Additive_colors.ogv/Additive_colors.ogv.240p.vp9.webm" type="video/webm; codecs=&quot;vp9, opus&quot;" data-transcodekey="240p.vp9.webm" data-width="426" data-height="240" /></video></span><figcaption>Additive color mixing demonstrated with CD covers used as <a href="/wiki/Beam_splitter" title="Beam splitter">beam splitters</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Venn_diagram_rgb.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Venn_diagram_rgb.svg/250px-Venn_diagram_rgb.svg.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="244" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Venn_diagram_rgb.svg/500px-Venn_diagram_rgb.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="500" /></a><figcaption>A diagram demonstrating additive color with RGB</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>RGB color model</b> is an <a href="/wiki/Additive_color" title="Additive color">additive</a> <a href="/wiki/Color_model" title="Color model">color model</a><sup id="cite&#95;ref-:0&#95;1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-1"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>1<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> in which the <a href="/wiki/Red" title="Red">red</a>, <a href="/wiki/Green" title="Green">green</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Blue" title="Blue">blue</a> <a href="/wiki/Primary_color" title="Primary color">primary colors</a> of light are added together in various ways to reproduce a broad array of <a href="/wiki/Color" title="Color">colors</a>. The name of the model comes from the initials of the three <a href="/wiki/Additive_primary_colors" class="mw-redirect" title="Additive primary colors">additive primary colors</a>— red, green, and blue.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The main purpose of the RGB color model is for the sensing, representation, and display of images in electronic systems, such as televisions and computers, though it has also been used in conventional <a href="/wiki/Photography" title="Photography">photography</a> and <a href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode#RGB_systems" title="Light-emitting diode">colored lighting</a>. Before the <a href="/wiki/Electronic_age" class="mw-redirect" title="Electronic age">electronic age</a>, the RGB color model already had a solid theory behind it, based in <a href="/wiki/Trichromacy" title="Trichromacy">human perception of colors</a>.
</p><p>RGB is a <i>device-dependent</i> color model: different devices detect or reproduce a given RGB value differently, since the color elements (such as <a href="/wiki/Phosphor" title="Phosphor">phosphors</a> or <a href="/wiki/Dye" title="Dye">dyes</a>) and their response to the individual red, green, and blue levels vary from manufacturer to manufacturer, or even in the same device over time. Thus an RGB value does not define the same <i>color</i> across devices without some kind of <a href="/wiki/Color_management" title="Color management">color management</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>3<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>4<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Typical RGB <a href="/wiki/Input_device" title="Input device">input devices</a> are color <a href="/wiki/Professional_video_camera" title="Professional video camera">TV and video cameras</a>, <a href="/wiki/Image_scanner" title="Image scanner">image scanners</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Digital_camera" title="Digital camera">digital cameras</a>. Typical RGB <a href="/wiki/Output_device" title="Output device">output devices</a> are TV sets of various technologies (<a href="/wiki/Cathode-ray_tube" class="mw-redirect" title="Cathode-ray tube">CRT</a>, <a href="/wiki/LCD_television" title="LCD television">LCD</a>, <a href="/wiki/Plasma_display" title="Plasma display">plasma</a>, <a href="/wiki/OLED" title="OLED">OLED</a>, <a href="/wiki/Quantum_dot_display" title="Quantum dot display">quantum dots</a>, etc.), <a href="/wiki/Computer_display" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer display">computer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Mobile_phone" title="Mobile phone">mobile phone</a> displays, <a href="/wiki/Video_projector" title="Video projector">video projectors</a>, multicolor <a href="/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" title="Light-emitting diode">LED</a> displays and large screens such as the <a href="/wiki/Jumbotron" title="Jumbotron">Jumbotron</a>. <a href="/wiki/Printer_(computing)" title="Printer (computing)">Color printers</a>, on the other hand, are not RGB devices, but <a href="/wiki/Subtractive_color" title="Subtractive color">subtractive color</a> devices typically using the <a href="/wiki/CMYK_color_model" title="CMYK color model">CMYK color model</a>.
</p>
